ISYE 6402 Homework 6 Solutions

Background

Individual stock prices tend to exhibit high amounts of non-constant variance, and thus ARIMA models built upon that data would likely exhibit non-constant variance in residuals. In this problem we are going to analyze the Intel stock price data from 2012 through end of 2021. We will use the ARIMA-GARCH to model daily and weekly stock price (adjusted close price at the end of a day for daily data or at the end of the week for weekly data), with a focus on the behavior of its volatility as well as forecasting both the price and the volatility.

##Data import and cleaning

#prices to timeseries format
INTWeekly <- ts(weeklydata$Adj.Close,start=c(2012,1,1),freq=52)
INTDaily <- ts(dailydata$Adj.Close,start=c(2012,1,1),freq=252)

#Question 1: Exploratory Data Analysis (20 points)

1a. Based on your intuition, when would you use daily vs weekly stock price data?

Response: Question 1a

We would use daily level data when a more granular analysis is needed. The is generally the case when focus i on shorter term outcome. In the scenarios when data fluctuates quickly (high volatility) we would prefer to examine the variance in these observations. However when looking for longer horizon forecasts, having the weekly vie makes sense as it will smoothn the variance at daily level.

1b. Plot the time series plots comparing daily vs weekly data. How do the daily vs weekly time series data compare?

ts.plot(INTDaily, main="Daily Stock Prices")

ts.plot(INTWeekly, main = "Weekly Stock Prices")

Response: Question 1b

  • The time series is non-stationary and nonlinear trend. There is minimalist seasonality in both daily and weekly pattern. Weekly is smooth view of Daily view with lesser variance.
  • the daily can be used for a more granular analysis, specifically when the short term changes are of more relevance. In case when data fluctuates quickly (high volatility), we would prefer to gauge the variance in these observations. The disadvantages of using the daily data verses weekly data would be introducing more volatile than needed when less granular analysis (e.g. weekly predictions) is of interest.

1c. Fit a non-parametric trend using splines regression to both the daily and weekly time-series data. Overlay the fitted trends. How do the trends compare?

points_daily = 1:NROW(INTDaily)
points_daily = (points_daily - min(points_daily))/max(points_daily)

points_weekly = 1:NROW(INTWeekly)
points_weekly = (points_weekly - min(points_weekly))/max(points_weekly)

gam.daily = gam(INTDaily ~s(points_daily))
gam.weekly = gam(INTWeekly ~s(points_weekly))

gam.daily.fit = ts(fitted(gam.daily), start=c(2012,1,1),freq=252)
gam.weekly.fit = ts(fitted(gam.weekly), start=c(2012,1,1),freq=52)

ts.plot(INTDaily, main = "Daily and Weekly Spline Fit")
lines(INTWeekly, col='green', lwd=2)
lines(gam.daily.fit, col='red', lwd=2)
lines(gam.weekly.fit, col = 'blue', lwd=2)

legend("topleft", legend = c("Daily", "Weekly", "Daily_fit", "Weekly_fit"), col=c("black", "green", "red", "blue"), lwd =2 )

Response: Question 1c

  • Both Daily and Weekly Trends fit the trend quite comparably. Daily fit (red) is capturing a bit more details in the trend vs Weekly. This has a lot to do with fact that weekly data has less variance. Overall trend estimation captures overall pattern, regardless of the granularity of the data.

#Question 2: ARIMA(p,d,q) for Stock Price (20 Points)

2a. Divide the data into training and testing data set, where the training data exclude the last week of data (December 27th - December 30th) with the testing data including the last week of data. Apply the iterative model to fit an ARIMA(p,d,q) model with max AR and MA orders of 8 and difference orders 1 and 2 separately to the training datasets of the daily and weekly data. Display the summary of the final model fit.

daily.train = INTDaily[1:(length(INTDaily)-4)]
daily.test = INTDaily[(length(INTDaily)-4+1):length(INTDaily)]

weekly.train = INTWeekly[1:(length(INTWeekly)-1)]
weekly.test = INTWeekly[length(INTWeekly):length(INTWeekly)]
n = length(daily.train)
norder = 8
p = 1:norder -1
q = 1:norder -1
aic = matrix(0, norder, norder)
for (i in 1:norder){
  for (j in 1:norder) {
    modij = arima(daily.train, order = c(p[i], 1, q[j]), method = 'ML')
    aic[i, j] = modij$aic - 2*(p[i] + q[j]+1) + 2 *(p[i] + q[j] +1) * n / (n-p[i]-q[j]-2)
  }
}
aicv = as.vector(aic)
plot(aicv, ylab="AIC values")

indexp <- rep(c(1:norder), norder)
indexq <- rep(c(1:norder), each = norder)
indexaic <- which(aicv == min(aicv))
porder_1 <- indexp[indexaic] - 1
qorder_1 <- indexq[indexaic] - 1
# Fit the "best" arima model
daily.final_model <- arima(daily.train,
                     order = c(porder_1, 1, qorder_1),
                     method = "ML")
summary(daily.final_model)

2b. Evaluate the model residuals and squared residuals using the ACF and PACF plots as well as hypothesis testing for serial correlation. What would you conclude based on this analysis?

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))

resids <- resid(daily.final_model)
plot(resids,
     ylab = 'Residuals',
     type = 'o',
     main = "Daily Residual Plot")
abline(h = 0)
hist(resids, xlab = 'Daily Residuals', main = 'Histogram: Residuals')
acf(resids, main = "Daily: Residuals")
pacf(resids, main = "Daily: Residuals")

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))

resids <- resid(weekly.final_model)
plot(resids,
     ylab = 'Residuals',
     type = 'o',
     main = "Weekly Residual Plot")
abline(h = 0)
hist(resids, xlab = 'Weekly Residuals', main = 'Histogram: Residuals')
acf(resids, main = "Weekly:  Residuals")
pacf(resids, main = "Weekly: Residuals")

Box.test(
  daily.final_model$resid,
  lag = (porder_1 + qorder_1 + 1),
  type = "Box-Pierce",
  fitdf = (porder_1 + qorder_1)
)
## 
##  Box-Pierce test
## 
## data:  daily.final_model$resid
## X-squared = 18.927, df = 1, p-value = 1.358e-05
Box.test(
  weekly.final_model$resid,
  lag = (porder_2 + qorder_2 + 1),
  type = "Box-Pierce",
  fitdf = (porder_2 + qorder_2)
)
## 
##  Box-Pierce test
## 
## data:  weekly.final_model$resid
## X-squared = 4.5992, df = 1, p-value = 0.03199

Response: Question 2b

  • The fit for the weekly data seems to be somewhat better fitting as assessed using the residual plots. The ACF and PACF plots resemble that of white noise. the scatter plot of daily show hetroskedasticity in the residuals, as well as the lags outside of the confidence bands.

  • Serial correlation output: The null hypothesis is that the residual process consists of uncorrelated variables. if p-value is small than 0.05 then we reject the null hypothesis. for both daily and weekly grain the p-value is less than 0.05 hence the residual does not consists of uncorrelated variables.

Question 3: ARMA(p,q)-GARCH(m,n) for Return Stock Price (20 Points)

3a. Divide the data into training and testing data set, where the training data exclude the last week of data (December 27th - December 30th) with the testing data including the last week of data. Apply the iterative model to fit an ARMA(p,q)-GARCH(m,n) model by selecting the orders for p & q up to 5 and orders for m & n up to 2. Display the summary of the final model fit. Write up the equation of the estimated model.

  • Daily *
test_modelAGG <- function(m,n, func_data, p, q){
    spec = ugarchspec(variance.model=list(garchOrder=c(m,n)),
                      mean.model=list(armaOrder=c(p,q),
                                      include.mean=T),
                      distribution.model="std")
    fit = ugarchfit(spec, func_data, solver = 'hybrid')
    current.bic = infocriteria(fit)[2]
    df = data.frame(m,n,current.bic)
    names(df) <- c("m","n","BIC")
    print(paste(m,n,current.bic,sep=" "))
    return(df)
}

test_modelAGA <- function(m, n, func_data, p,q){
    spec = ugarchspec(variance.model=list(garchOrder=c(m,n)),

                                      include.mean=T),

    df = data.frame(p,q,current.bic)
    names(df) <- c("p","q","BIC")
    print(paste(p,q,current.bic,sep=" "))
    return(df)
}

3c. Apply the model identified in (3a) and forecast the mean and the variance of the last week of data. Plot the predicted data to compare the predicted values to the actual observed ones. Interpret the results, particularly comparing forecast using daily versus weekly data.

  • Daily
nfore = length(daily.test)
fore.series.1 = NULL
fore.sigma.1 = NULL
for(f in 1: nfore){
    ## Fit models
    data = daily.train
    if(f>2)
       data = c(daily.train,daily.test[1:(f-1)])
    final.model.1 = ugarchfit(spec.1, data, solver = 'hybrid')
    ## Forecast
    fore = ugarchforecast(final.model.1, n.ahead=1)
    fore.series.1 = c(fore.series.1, fore@forecast$seriesFor)
    fore.sigma.1 = c(fore.sigma.1, fore@forecast$sigmaFor)
   
}

Question 4: Reflection on the Modeling and Forecasting (10 points)

Based on the analysis above, discuss the application of ARIMA on the stock price versus the application of ARMA-GARCH on the stock return. How do the models fit the data? How well do the models predict? How do the models perform when using daily versus weekly data? Would you use one approach over another for different settings? What are some specific points of caution one would need to consider when applying those models?

Response: Question 4

ARMA-GARCH is able to better fit the data as seems to handle volatility. This is evident from lower MAP for ARMA-GARCH at 0.008 vs ARIMA 0.015. Between Daily and Weekly, Weekly performed better with lower MAPE vs Daily Model. This might due to lower variance and much smoothen data. As we saw that squared residuals from ARIMA model were correlated. Moreover the volatility had non-linear trends. So it is needed to model the non-constant variability or hetroskedasity where conditional variance could change over time. Hence family of ARCH models by Robert Engle which could model time-varying volatility are useful. However a more generalized approach called GARCH, where negative and positive shocks have different effect on volatility and overcome other assumptions of ARCH is preferred.
